# ── Spotify API credentials ────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Create a free app at https://developer.spotify.com/dashboard
#
# When creating the app, Spotify asks for a Redirect URI.
# Use:  http://127.0.0.1:6767/api/spotify/callback
#
# Rules (per developer.spotify.com/documentation/web-api/concepts/redirect_uri):
#   - localhost is NOT allowed
#   - Must be explicit IPv4/IPv6 loopback with a port: http://127.0.0.1:PORT
#   - After adding the redirect URI, go to Settings → Connect Spotify Account
#     in the web UI. You will be redirected to Spotify to log in once.
#     Tokens are stored in the container volume and auto-refreshed.
#
# When asked "Which API/SDKs are you planning to use?", select:
#   ✔ Web API  (only this one — nothing else is needed)
SPOTIFY_CLIENT_ID=your_client_id_here
SPOTIFY_CLIENT_SECRET=your_client_secret_here

# ── Music output directory ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Absolute path on your HOST machine that will be mounted into the container
MUSIC_DIR=/absolute/path/to/your/music/folder

# ── YouTube cookies (optional but recommended) ────────────────────────────
# If you see "Sign in to confirm you're not a bot" errors, export your
# YouTube cookies and mount them into the container.
#
# How to export:
#   1. Install the "Get cookies.txt LOCALLY" extension in Chrome/Firefox
#   2. Go to https://www.youtube.com while logged in (or not — logged-out
#      cookies also help bypass bot detection)
#   3. Click the extension and export cookies.txt
#   4. Place the file anywhere on your host, then add this line under
#      backend → volumes in docker-compose.yml:
#        - /path/to/cookies.txt:/data/cookies.txt:ro
#
# The container automatically uses /data/cookies.txt if it exists.
#
# Set COOKIES_PATH to the absolute path of your cookies.txt on this machine.
# Leave it commented out (or empty) to skip cookies — a harmless empty
# placeholder file will be mounted instead.
# COOKIES_PATH=/absolute/path/to/cookies.txt
